#
#  Maintained by Zenn.dev / Classmethod (zenn-dev/zenn-editor).  740
#  GH stars.  Zenn is a Japanese developer blogging / technical
#  documentation publishing platform — similar to Dev.to / Medium /
#  Hashnode but with a STRONG GITHUB-FIRST WORKFLOW where authors
#  store Markdown content in a GitHub repo and Zenn auto-publishes
#  to their account.  `zenn` is the local-preview CLI that renders
#  the same Markdown→HTML conversion as the Zenn web app, plus
#  scaffolds new articles/books with frontmatter.  Sister tools:
#  Hugo / Jekyll (static site generators, IN CORPUS via _hugo /
#  _jekyll), Astro (in corpus via _astro), VuePress, Hexo.
#
#  CLI library taxonomy update: 10th TypeScript-Node CLI library —
#  Vercel's **arg** (vercel/arg).  TypeScript-Node ecosystem now has
#  10 documented CLI libraries — TYING Rust (10) and Go (10) for
#  FIRST-MOST-DOCUMENTED CLI LANGUAGE at the TOP TIER of the cross-
#  language CLI library taxonomy.  🎉 TypeScript-Node JOINS Rust and
#  Go for a THREE-WAY TIE AT 10 (each at the top).
#
#  arg (vercel/arg) is Vercel's TYPESCRIPT-NATIVE minimalist arg
#  parser — ~3KB, zero dependencies, TYPE COERCION via JavaScript
#  CONSTRUCTORS (`Number`/`String`/`Boolean`).  Used by Prisma
#  (next-gen TypeScript ORM, IN CORPUS via _prisma — 46k stars),
#  Vercel/micro (asynchronous HTTP microservices, IN CORPUS via
#  _micro — 10k stars), Expo (universal React Native framework, IN
#  CORPUS via _expo — 49k stars), Astro framework (upgrade tool),
#  Zenn (developer blogging platform, this binary, 740 stars),
#  Temporal SDK build scripts, NodeScript module-generator,
#  rafamel/yaml-import, francisashley/shard-docs, decentraland/
#  opscli, kyanvasu/andromeda-cli, lys-lang/lys compiler, and many
#  TypeScript-first projects in the Vercel/Next.js ecosystem.
#
#  arg API:
#    import arg from 'arg';
#
#    try {
#      const args = arg(
#        {
#          // Types via JS constructors (Number/String/Boolean/Date)
#          '--port':    Number,
#          '--config':  String,
#          '--verbose': Boolean,
#
#          // Array types via [Type] for repeated
#          '--include': [String],
#          '--counts':  [Number],
#
#          // Custom type via function (val, name, prev) => coerced
#          '--date':    (val) => new Date(val),
#
#          // Aliases (short → long mapping via STRING value)
#          '-p':        '--port',
#          '-c':        '--config',
#          '-v':        '--verbose',
#          '-I':        '--include',
#        },
#        {
#          // Optional: explicit argv
#          argv: process.argv.slice(2),
#
#          // Allow unknown args (pass through to _)
#          permissive: true,
#
#          // Stop parsing at first positional
#          stopAtPositional: false,
#        }
#      );
#
#      // Access parsed values:
#      console.log(args['--port']);     // number
#      console.log(args['--include']);  // string[]
#      console.log(args._);              // positional args array
#    } catch (err) {
#      if (err.code === 'ARG_UNKNOWN_OPTION') {
#        console.error('Unknown:', err.message);
#      } else if (err.code === 'ARG_MISSING_REQUIRED_LONGARG') {
#        console.error('Missing:', err.message);
#      } else {
#        throw err;
#      }
#    }
#
#  vercel/arg distinctive features:
#    - TYPESCRIPT-NATIVE — written in TypeScript with full type
#      definitions; preserves narrow types via const-assertion on
#      schema objects (arg infers `args['--port']` as `number` based
#      on `'--port': Number` mapping to JS Number constructor)
#    - TYPE COERCION via JS CONSTRUCTORS — `Number`, `String`,
#      `Boolean`, `Date`, custom function (val, name, prev) =>
#      coerced (these are the SAME built-in constructors used in
#      regular JavaScript — distinct from minimist's `type: 'string'`
#      / `type: 'boolean'` config-key approach)
#    - ARRAY TYPES via `[Type]` — `'--include': [String]` collects
#      multiple occurrences into `string[]`
#    - SHORT-TO-LONG ALIASES via STRING VALUE — `'-p': '--port'`
#      means `-p` is an alias for `--port` (distinct from minimist's
#      `alias: { p: 'port' }` config)
#    - SCHEMA OBJECT — first argument is a single object mapping
#      `'--flag-name'` (FULL FLAG NAME WITH LEADING `--`) to type
#      constructor or alias string
#    - OPTIONS OBJECT (second argument):
#      * `argv` — explicit argv array (default: process.argv.slice(2))
#      * `permissive: true` — pass unknown args to `args._` instead
#        of throwing
#      * `stopAtPositional: true` — stop parsing at first positional
#        (useful for nested CLI dispatch like `npm run X --`)
#    - RESULT OBJECT:
#      * `args['--flag-name']` — parsed value with FULL FLAG NAME
#        KEY (kebab-case preserved; no automatic camelCase conversion)
#      * `args._` — positional args / extra args after first non-option
#    - ERROR CODES via thrown Error subclasses with `.code` property:
#      * `ARG_UNKNOWN_OPTION` — unknown flag (unless `permissive`)
#      * `ARG_MISSING_REQUIRED_LONGARG` — required flag missing value
#      * `ARG_MISSING_REQUIRED_SHORTARG` — required short flag missing
#      * `ARG_CONFIG_VAD_PROPS` — schema validation error
#      * `ARG_CONFIG_EMPTY_ARG` — empty arg name in schema
#      * `ARG_CONFIG_SHORTOPT_TOOLONG` — short opt longer than 1 char
#    - NO subcommand support — caller hand-rolls subcommand dispatch
#      (zenn does this: `args._[0]` becomes the subcommand name)
#    - NO automatic --help/--version — caller writes manually (zenn
#      adds `'--help': Boolean` to schema)
#    - DEFAULT EXPORT — `import arg from 'arg'` (ESM) / `const arg =
#      require('arg')` (CommonJS)
#    - TINY ~3KB minified, ZERO DEPENDENCIES
#    - VERCEL-MAINTAINED — used by Vercel CLI, Next.js's compiled
#      binary tools, and many Vercel-team open-source projects
#  Distinct from R340 TypeScript-Node oclif (Salesforce's CLI
#  framework — much heavier framework), R341 TypeScript-Node yargs
#  (Node.js fluent builder via `.option('name', {})`), R343
#  TypeScript-Node tj/commander.js (Node.js fluent builder by TJ
#  Holowaychuk — fluent API vs schema object), R393 TypeScript-Node
#  meow (Sindre Sorhus's CLI helper with usage-string + flags
#  schema), R395 node:util.parseArgs (Node.js stdlib — schema with
#  `type: 'string'`/`'boolean'` keys vs arg's constructor functions),
#  R396 TypeScript-Node sade (Luke Edwards's TINY commander
#  alternative with subcommands), R400 TypeScript-Node cac (EGOIST's
#  "Command And Conquer" with subcommands and patterns), R402
#  TypeScript-Node minimist (substack's original ~1KB; `alias`/
#  `string`/`boolean` config keys vs arg's schema object), R403
#  TypeScript-Node clipanion (TYPESCRIPT-FIRST + CLASS-BASED with
#  `class extends Command`).  arg's approach: TYPESCRIPT-NATIVE
#  minimalist arg parser + SCHEMA OBJECT mapping `'--flag-name'`
#  (full flag name with leading `--`) to type CONSTRUCTOR (Number/
#  String/Boolean/Date/custom-function) or ALIAS STRING + ARRAY
#  TYPES via `[Type]` for repeated + OPTIONS OBJECT 2nd arg with
#  `argv`/`permissive`/`stopAtPositional` keys + RESULT OBJECT with
#  `args['--flag-name']` full-flag-name keys (kebab-case preserved)
#  and `args._` positional + ERROR CODES via thrown Error subclasses
#  + NO subcommand support / NO automatic --help/--version (caller
#  hand-rolls) + TINY ~3KB ZERO DEPENDENCIES — corpus's **first
#  documented schema-object-with-constructor-typed Node.js CLI
#  library**.  Brings cross-language CLI library taxonomy variant
#  count to 145; TypeScript-Node ecosystem now has 10 documented
#  CLI libraries — TYING Rust (10) and Go (10) for FIRST-MOST-
#  DOCUMENTED CLI LANGUAGE at the TOP TIER of the cross-language
#  CLI library taxonomy.  🎉 THREE-WAY TIE AT 10.
#
#  Surface (verbatim from `packages/zenn-cli/src/server/zenn.ts`
#  dispatcher + per-command parseArgs schemas):
#
#  Subcommands (default: preview):
#
#    preview                        Start local preview server
#    -p, --port PORT                Listen port (default: 8000)
#        --no-watch                 Disable file watching
#        --open                     Open browser after start
#        --host HOST                Bind hostname
#    -h, --help                     Show preview command help
#
#    init                           Initialize Zenn directory structure
#                                   (creates articles/ and books/)
#    -h, --help                     Show init help
#
#    new:article                    Create a new article with frontmatter
#        --slug SLUG                Article slug (default: auto-generated)
#        --title TITLE              Article title
#        --type TYPE                Article type: tech | idea
#        --emoji EMOJI              Article emoji (default: random)
#        --published BOOL           Published state
#        --publication-name NAME    Publication name
#        --machine-readable         Output machine-readable result
#    -h, --help                     Show new:article help
#
#    new:book                       Create a new book with chapters
#        --slug SLUG                Book slug
#        --title TITLE              Book title
#        --published BOOL           Published state
#    -h, --help                     Show new:book help
#
#    list:articles                  List all articles in repo
#    -h, --help                     Show list:articles help
#
#    list:books                     List all books in repo
#    -h, --help                     Show list:books help
#
#    help                           Show general help
#    version                        Show version
#
#  Auto-injected by arg (none — caller writes manually):
#    All --help/--version dispatch is HAND-ROLLED by zenn-cli
#    (arg does not auto-inject; this is by design)
#
#  Configuration:
#    articles/*.md                  Article Markdown files (with
#                                   YAML frontmatter)
#    books/*/                       Book directories
#
#  Dup-skipped neighbors during hunt (in corpus or smaller user base,
#  also vercel/arg users):
#    - prisma (IN CORPUS via _prisma — next-gen TypeScript ORM 46041
#      stars; uses vercel/arg in scripts/bump-engines.ts and many
#      internal tools; already documented under different attribution;
#      flagship vercel/arg use case)
#    - micro (IN CORPUS via _micro — Vercel async HTTP microservices
#      10619 stars; uses vercel/arg; flagship use case)
#    - expo (IN CORPUS via _expo — React Native framework 49790
#      stars; uses vercel/arg in CLI)
#    - astro (withastro/astro — 50k+ stars; uses both arg and mri
#      across different tools; FUTURE candidate)
#    - temporalio/sdk-typescript (Temporal SDK build scripts, uses
#      arg; library not user-facing CLI)
#    - decentraland/opscli (decentraland 1 star — Decentraland nodes
